{"id":"1512.02500","submitter":"Eric R. Weeks","authors":"Xia Hong, Meghan Kohne, Mia Morrell, Haoran Wang, and Eric R. Weeks","title":"Clogging of soft particles in 2D hoppers","comments":"v03 has new experiments using hydrogel particles, along with new\n  coauthors who did those experiments","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 96, 062605 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.96.062605","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Using experiments and simulations, we study the flow of soft particles\nthrough quasi-two-dimensional hoppers. The first experiment uses oil-in-water\nemulsion droplets in a thin sample chamber. Due to surfactants coating the\ndroplets, they easily slide past each other, approximating soft frictionless\ndisks. For these droplets, clogging at the hopper exit requires a narrow hopper\nopening only slightly larger than the droplet diameter. The second experiments\nuse soft hydrogel particles in a thin sample chamber, where we vary gravity by\nchanging the tilt angle of the chamber. For reduced gravity, clogging becomes\neasier, and can occur for larger hopper openings. Our simulations mimic the\nemulsion experiments and demonstrate that softness is a key factor controlling\nclogging: with stiffer particles or a weaker gravitational force, clogging is\neasier. The fractional amount a single particle is deformed under its own\nweight is a useful parameter measuring particle softness. Data from the\nsimulation and hydrogel experiments collapse when compared using this\nparameter. Our results suggest that prior studies using hard particles were in\na limit where the role of softness is negligible which causes clogging to occur\nwith significantly larger openings.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 8 Dec 2015 15:11:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 15 Aug 2016 13:50:37 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 1 Nov 2017 17:12:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-12-14"}
